==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Description</span>==
{{Blurimage|file=Behind the Scenes.jpg|caption=The first photograph of '''Level 501''', taken on an unknown date.}}
Level 501 resembles 1940's Hollywood film sets. Level 501 mostly has a 1940s American Urban style setting, although there are various other settings it can turn into. The level commonly has 1940s filming equipment scattered throughout the level, some of which still functions. There are also 1940s-style cars scattered throughout the level, though most of them are proven to be prop cars. There are very rarely, however, functioning real cars at this level that can be driven, but the chances of finding one are almost non-existent, as there have only been eight recorded instances of finding these functioning cars.

The buildings in the level while having details on the outside, are almost completely bare on the inside. While one may find some details in the buildings, they are small and don't have any significance. One may also occasionally find filming equipment inside the buildings, none of which will be functioning with the exception of an exit one may come across.

There are portions of the level, however, that are more dangerous than the rest of the level, and that is the animation sections. The animation sections of the level are not designed for real human bodies. As such, if one enters the animated section, their bodies will become instantly animated and will forget who they are. One can notice the presence of an animated section nearby if they start hearing a pencil drawing something. 

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>The Animated Disease</span>===

The animation disease is a disease that one gets if they stay for more than three hours in the level, if their eyes see the animation section, or if Mr. Frown infects them with it. It is an irreversible disease that progresses for one hour. If one goes indoors, it can slow down the disease some, but only for 30 more minutes. And if one gets the disease, all exits will be blocked for them. And if one were with another person or in a group, they would not be allowed to exit the level as well, and they would also get the disease, as it is contagious and will spread rapidly.

Within the first 15 minutes of getting the disease, one will start experiencing hallucinations of the level being animated. They will also experience feelings of emptiness and a craving for something. Around 30 minutes after initial contact with the disease, one will start seeing themselves as animated. They will also start wanting to do things that are physically impossible for the human body. 

After 45 minutes pass, their bodies will finally start to take an animated form and will no longer be a hallucination to themselves. It is also at this point that they will start to forget their own identities; everyone they ever knew. At the one-hour mark, the disease will be in total control. Their memories will be altered to adopt a new cartoon identity, and their bodies will be able to do things that would otherwise have been impossible for their normal forms.

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Entities</span>==

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>The Actors</span>===

The Actors are neutral entities within the level that occasionally pop up within the level. They are often in groups of two or three, usually portraying a role of a character. Rarely they will be seen holding script papers, often reading from them and practicing what roles they have. It is also possible to see these actors in prop cars practicing their roles, although encountering them in these cars are very rare. The Actors will be wearing 1940s suits and will mostly likely be wearing fedoras as well.  
{{Blurimage|file=Actors at work.png|caption=An actor duo at work.}}
If one chooses to interact with the actors, they will usually be friendly and are willing to talk to wanderers about various things at first. Though they will avoid any discussion of the animated sections, The Animated Disease, and Mr. Frown. Around five minutes after one first talks to them, the actors will start to become uncomfortable and will say they have to get back to work. If one tries to persist that they want to talk further, the actors will become hostile and will tell them to back off. Any attempted interaction after that will fall on deaf ears.

===<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Mr. Frown</span>===

Mr. Frown is a hostile entity who will attack anyone on sight. He has the appearance of a World War one soldier, although he does not carry any sort of equipment. He appears to be an elderly man, and at first glance appears to move slowly. Also, he looks to be loudly mumbling, although what he is mumbling just appears to be pure gibberish. 

If Mr. Frown sees a wanderer, he will stop mumbling and aggressively chase them. When he first looks at a wanderer, he will produce a deafening scream in an attempt to stop the wanderer from fleeing. If that does not work, he will chase the wanderer down until he bites into them. If he manages to land a bite on the wanderer, they will gain The Animated Disease, and Mr. Frown will leave them alone. 
{{Blurimage|file=Mr. Frown.jpg|caption=An attempt by a wanderer outside the level to mimic his look.}}
Mr. Frown will also attempt to lure wanderers into the animated section. If he knows he cannot use his scream to deafen their ears or he cannot chase them down, he will start to walk towards the animated section. He will also silence the pencil drawing sounds in a further attempt to draw them in. It is thought Mr. Frown is the one who controls the animated sections of the level, and that he is the one who gives people infected by the Animation Disease their new identities and causes them to forget their old ones. 

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Groups and Organizations</span>==

Due to animated dangers within the level, colonies and outposts cannot be established. Though several groups have done excursions in the level in an attempt to study the animated properties of the level.

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Entrances and Exits</span>==

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Entrances</span>==

In [[Level 765]] if one manages to get a 1920s film camera from a Wibble-Whum Woggler and activates it, they will be brought here.

If one manages to find an abandoned 1940s car in [[Level 84]] and sit in it for one minute, they will be brought here.

In [[Level 444]] if one manages to find an out-of-place blue seat in an auditorium, sit in it and go to sleep, they will wake up here.

In [[Level 507]] if one manages to find a wooden door with a film reel logo on it and enters it, they will be brought here.

In [[Level 125]] if one manages to find grey lights on a house and enters that house, they will be brought here.

==<span style="font-family:Broadway; color: #757575;>Exits</span>==

If one sees an active film camera in a building displaying a movie and walks through that screen, they will end up in [[Level 444]].

If one successfully manages to talk to an actor about getting out of the level, they will point to a building. Enter that building and one will find an out-of-place green door. Enter that door and one will end up in [[Level 13]].

If one manages to find a manhole cover under a prop car, move that prop car out of the way and enter that manhole, they will be taken to [[Level 248]].

